ArcticDownloader 0.1.5 update log

Purpose:
- Track code changes made in the Linux workspace so they can be mirrored in the Windows workspace.

Format:
- Date
- Change summary
- Files changed
- Notes

Entries:
- 2026-03-12
  - Initialized this tracking file for upcoming 0.1.5 bug fixes and enhancements.
  - Files changed:
    - version0.1.5_updates
  - Notes:
    - No application code changes yet.
- 2026-03-12
  - Fixed ComfyUI/PyTorch runtime compatibility warning caused by the deprecated `PYTORCH_CUDA_ALLOC_CONF` environment variable being inherited by spawned Python processes.
  - Files changed:
    - src-tauri/src/main.rs
    - version0.1.5_updates
  - Notes:
    - Added a Python process environment compatibility helper.
    - If `PYTORCH_CUDA_ALLOC_CONF` is present and `PYTORCH_ALLOC_CONF` is not, the app now copies the value to `PYTORCH_ALLOC_CONF`.
    - The app removes `PYTORCH_CUDA_ALLOC_CONF` from child Python processes to avoid the PyTorch deprecation warning.
    - Applied this to ComfyUI launch, Python runtime detection, and torch profile verification commands.
- 2026-03-12
  - Added an "Enable Server on Launch (--listen)" checkbox for managed ComfyUI installs so users can start ComfyUI with the `--listen` flag from the app.
  - Files changed:
    - src/config.rs
    - src-tauri/src/main.rs
    - src-tauri/dist/index.html
    - src-tauri/dist/main.js
    - version0.1.5_updates
  - Notes:
    - Added a persisted `comfyui_listen_enabled` setting with default `false`.
    - ComfyUI launch arguments now include `--listen` when that setting is enabled.
    - Added a UI checkbox labeled `Enable Server on Launch (--listen)`.
    - The checkbox state is loaded from saved settings and can be toggled from the existing ComfyUI manage flow.
- 2026-03-12
  - Refined the ComfyUI launch controls by adding a dedicated `Flags` section below `Custom-Nodes` and separating install state from launch state.
  - Files changed:
    - src-tauri/src/main.rs
    - src-tauri/dist/index.html
    - src-tauri/dist/main.js
    - version0.1.5_updates
  - Notes:
    - Added a `Flags` section with launch toggles for `SageAttention`, `SageAttention3`, `FlashAttention`, and `--listen`.
    - Add-On checkboxes now represent what is installed, while Flag checkboxes represent what should be enabled when ComfyUI starts.
    - Installing `SageAttention`, `SageAttention3`, or `FlashAttention` still enables the matching launch flag by default.
    - Users can now keep those add-ons installed but disable their launch flags temporarily to start ComfyUI without them.
    - Added a new backend command to change launch attention flags without reinstalling or removing the add-ons.
- 2026-03-12
  - Updated the `Flags` section labels to show the actual ComfyUI CLI flags instead of descriptive "Launch with ..." text.
  - Files changed:
    - src-tauri/dist/index.html
    - src-tauri/dist/main.js
    - version0.1.5_updates
  - Notes:
    - Changed visible labels to `--use-sage-attention`, `--use-flash-attention`, and `--listen`.
    - Aligned the `--listen` confirmation text with the new label.
- 2026-03-12
  - Simplified the `Flags` section by removing the duplicate SageAttention3 entry because SageAttention and SageAttention3 use the same visible ComfyUI flag.
  - Files changed:
    - src-tauri/dist/index.html
    - src-tauri/dist/main.js
    - version0.1.5_updates
  - Notes:
    - The UI now shows a single `--use-sage-attention` checkbox.
    - That single checkbox reflects either saved Sage launch mode (`sage` or `sage3`).
    - When users enable the Sage flag, the UI maps it to `sage3` if SageAttention3 is the installed Sage backend; otherwise it maps to regular `sage`.
- 2026-03-12
  - Clarified the ComfyUI runtime log message for the default attention path.
  - Files changed:
    - src-tauri/src/main.rs
    - version0.1.5_updates
  - Notes:
    - When no special attention backend flag is active, the log now says `Launching with attention backend: PyTorch attention` instead of `none`.
- 2026-03-12
  - Added a manual AMD ROCm install option for the Linux ComfyUI installer.
  - Files changed:
    - src-tauri/src/main.rs
    - src-tauri/dist/main.js
    - version0.1.5_updates
  - Notes:
    - Added a new torch profile option: `Torch 2.9.1 + ROCm 6.4`.
    - The installer now installs that profile from the PyTorch ROCm wheel index and detects/verifies ROCm runtime versions correctly.
    - ROCm installs skip the CUDA-specific Triton package step used by the CUDA profiles.
    - Added guardrails so CUDA-only add-ons in this app (`SageAttention`, `SageAttention3`, `FlashAttention`, `Nunchaku`, and `Trellis2`) are blocked for ROCm profiles.
    - Updated the UI recommendation copy so AMD users are told to select the ROCm profile manually instead of seeing a misleading CUDA recommendation.
- 2026-03-12
  - Added AMD GPU auto-detection for the Linux ComfyUI installer so ROCm is selected automatically and CUDA torch profiles are disabled.
  - Files changed:
    - src-tauri/src/main.rs
    - src-tauri/dist/main.js
    - version0.1.5_updates
  - Notes:
    - Added lightweight AMD GPU detection on Linux using `lspci`.
    - If an AMD GPU is detected, the installer now recommends and auto-selects `Torch 2.9.1 + ROCm 6.4`.
    - When AMD is detected, NVIDIA/CUDA torch profiles are disabled in the dropdown so the user cannot pick them.
    - Updated the title/system GPU text to show AMD GPU detection in the UI.
- 2026-03-12
  - Restricted the ROCm torch profile for detected NVIDIA systems.
  - Files changed:
    - src-tauri/dist/main.js
    - version0.1.5_updates
  - Notes:
    - If an NVIDIA GPU is detected, the ROCm torch profile is now disabled in the installer dropdown.
    - If the UI somehow lands on the ROCm profile while NVIDIA is detected, it falls back to a CUDA profile automatically.
- 2026-03-12
  - Added guided ROCm setup support for AMD users on supported Linux distro families.
  - Files changed:
    - src-tauri/src/main.rs
    - src-tauri/dist/index.html
    - src-tauri/dist/main.js
    - version0.1.5_updates
  - Notes:
    - Added a ROCm status row in the ComfyUI installer UI with `Check ROCm` and `Guided ROCm Setup` actions.
    - Added backend ROCm readiness checks covering `rocminfo`, `/dev/kfd`, and current user group membership (`render`/`video`).
    - Added guided ROCm setup flows for supported distro families:
      - Debian-based systems: installs AMD's `amdgpu-install` package and runs the ROCm usecase installer.
      - Fedora: installs ROCm packages with `dnf`.
      - Arch: installs ROCm packages with `pacman`.
    - Added ROCm preflight validation so the ComfyUI installer blocks ROCm installs until the system runtime looks ready.
    - Guided setup may still require logout/login or reboot before ROCm becomes usable.
- 2026-03-12
  - Added safe AMD simulation mode and more detailed ROCm setup logging.
  - Files changed:
    - src-tauri/src/main.rs
    - version0.1.5_updates
    - CHANGELOG_0.1.5.md
  - Notes:
    - Added `--fakeamd` launch flag for UI testing on non-AMD systems.
    - Fake AMD mode enables the AMD/ROCm UI path but disables the real guided ROCm installer to avoid modifying NVIDIA/non-AMD machines.
    - Guided ROCm setup now emits step-by-step progress messages into the existing ComfyUI log stream.
- 2026-03-12
  - Added a human-readable 0.1.5 changelog file for release notes and cross-platform handoff.
  - Files changed:
    - CHANGELOG_0.1.5.md
    - version0.1.5_updates
  - Notes:
    - Summarizes the implemented fixes and enhancements in user-facing language.
- 2026-03-12
  - Updated the Linux release build script to automatically use the root changelog file as release notes.
  - Files changed:
    - scripts/build-release-linux.sh
    - version0.1.5_updates
  - Notes:
    - If `CHANGELOG_<version>.md` exists in the repo root, the script now uses it automatically as the notes file.
    - `--notes-file` still works and overrides the default behavior.
    - The script now extracts a cleaner summary line from the markdown file for Debian changelog generation instead of using the markdown title line verbatim.
- 2026-03-12
  - Fixed the ComfyUI installer torch profile reset when switching from `Manage Existing` back to `Install New`.
  - Files changed:
    - src-tauri/dist/main.js
    - version0.1.5_updates
  - Notes:
    - If AMD is detected, switching back to `Install New` now restores the ROCm torch profile in the dropdown instead of leaving the previously managed install profile selected.
    - This keeps the dropdown aligned with the AMD auto-selection message and ROCm-only profile restrictions.
- 2026-03-12
  - Adjusted fake AMD mode so ROCm preflight does not block installer flow during UI/testing sessions.
  - Files changed:
    - src-tauri/src/main.rs
    - version0.1.5_updates
  - Notes:
    - In `--fakeamd` mode, ROCm readiness is now simulated as ready for preflight purposes.
    - Guided ROCm setup remains disabled in fake AMD mode to avoid modifying a non-AMD system.
    - This allows testing the AMD/ROCm install flow on NVIDIA or non-AMD machines without hitting a blocking ROCm runtime failure.
- 2026-03-12
  - Added an explicit override so fake AMD mode can run the real guided ROCm package install when requested.
  - Files changed:
    - src-tauri/src/main.rs
    - version0.1.5_updates
  - Notes:
    - Added `--fakeamd-allow-rocm-setup` for testing the real guided ROCm package installation flow on non-AMD systems.
    - Default `--fakeamd` behavior stays safe and keeps guided ROCm setup disabled.
    - When the override flag is present, the app no longer fakes ROCm readiness and instead runs the normal guided setup/preflight behavior.
- 2026-03-12
  - Corrected ROCm preflight messaging so fresh AMD users are not told to log out or reboot before ROCm is actually installed.
  - Files changed:
    - src-tauri/src/main.rs
    - version0.1.5_updates
  - Notes:
    - The ROCm preflight now only marks the situation as a relogin/reboot case when ROCm runtime components appear to be partially present but the current user session has not picked up the required `render`/`video` group membership yet.
    - A fully missing ROCm install now stays in the normal “runtime is not ready” path instead of the misleading “log out and back in” path.
- 2026-03-12
  - Made ROCm failure messaging explicit and actionable for fresh AMD installs.
  - Files changed:
    - src-tauri/src/main.rs
    - version0.1.5_updates
  - Notes:
    - When ROCm is missing or incomplete, the status/preflight message now explicitly says so and tells the user to run `Guided ROCm Setup`, then run the ROCm check again.
    - The relogin/reboot wording is now reserved for post-install session refresh cases only.
- 2026-03-12
  - Shortened ROCm status text so the installer UI row stays readable.
  - Files changed:
    - src-tauri/src/main.rs
    - version0.1.5_updates
  - Notes:
    - The ROCm status row now uses a concise summary instead of appending all low-level readiness notes into one long sentence.
    - Missing/incomplete ROCm now shows a short “Run Guided ROCm Setup, then Check ROCm again” message.
- 2026-03-12
  - Streamed guided ROCm installation command output into the GUI log and made auth/group-update failures visible.
  - Files changed:
    - src-tauri/src/main.rs
    - version0.1.5_updates
  - Notes:
    - Guided ROCm setup now forwards live `pacman`/`dnf`/`apt`/`pkexec`/`sudo` command output into the existing ComfyUI install log panel.
    - The app now logs when passwordless sudo is unavailable, when it falls back to PolicyKit, and when terminal sudo authentication is required.
    - The render/video group update step now logs warnings if it fails instead of failing silently.
- 2026-03-12
  - Reduced repeated sudo prompts during guided ROCm setup.
  - Files changed:
    - src-tauri/src/main.rs
    - version0.1.5_updates
  - Notes:
    - Guided ROCm setup now runs each distro workflow as a single privileged shell session instead of several separate root commands.
    - This reduces repeated sudo prompts and keeps the package-manager output in one continuous GUI log stream.
- 2026-03-12
  - Removed an unused guided ROCm helper after consolidating the workflow into a single privileged shell path.
  - Files changed:
    - src-tauri/src/main.rs
    - version0.1.5_updates
  - Notes:
    - Cleans up the Rust warning about the unused `run_privileged_command_streaming` function during `cargo tauri dev`.
- 2026-03-12
  - Fixed ROCm readiness detection on Arch and clarified fake AMD install-test completion status.
  - Files changed:
    - src-tauri/src/main.rs
    - version0.1.5_updates
  - Notes:
    - The app now detects `rocminfo` from `/opt/rocm/bin/rocminfo` when it is installed there but not present in the default shell `PATH`.
    - In `--fakeamd --fakeamd-allow-rocm-setup` mode, a successful package install no longer ends with a misleading runtime-failure message tied to missing real AMD hardware.
    - Fake AMD install-test mode now reports that runtime validation is intentionally skipped because no real AMD GPU is present.
- 2026-03-12
  - Moved guided ROCm setup off the UI thread to prevent the app from appearing frozen during long distro-specific install steps.
  - Files changed:
    - src-tauri/src/main.rs
    - version0.1.5_updates
  - Notes:
    - `install_rocm_guided` is now executed through `tokio::task::spawn_blocking`.
    - This keeps the window responsive while package-manager and privileged setup commands are running.
- 2026-03-12
  - Improved guided ROCm setup responsiveness in the UI so users see immediate feedback after clicking the action.
  - Files changed:
    - src-tauri/dist/main.js
    - version0.1.5_updates
  - Notes:
    - The UI now logs `Starting guided ROCm setup...` immediately and yields a paint frame before invoking the backend command.
    - This reduces the dead-window feel during the first seconds of Fedora/Ubuntu guided setup.
